From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] acpi/osl: PS4 - revert SCI install to non-threaded request_irq

ROOT CAUSE for PS4 6.x HDMI display being broken since the start of
this port.

In 6.x kernels, acpi_os_install_interrupt_handler uses:
  request_threaded_irq(irq, NULL, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED | IRQF_ONESHOT,
                       "acpi", acpi_irq)

In 5.4, it used:
  request_irq(irq, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED, "acpi", acpi_irq)

On PS4 (Baikal southbridge), IRQ9 is shared with another peripheral
that uses non-ONESHOT semantics.  Registering an ONESHOT handler as
a SHARED action gets rejected by the kernel ->
"SCI (IRQ9) allocation failed" -> AE_NOT_ACQUIRED ->
SCI handler isn't installed -> ACPI mutex initialization is incomplete
-> ATOM BIOS calls return AE_BAD_PARAMETER from
acpi_os_wait_semaphore (the underlying mutex impl) ->
amdgpu_atombios_crtc_adjust_pll returns 0 ->
amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_pll programs garbage values ->
GPU PLL/DP-TX broken -> HDMI bridge can't lock -> blank monitor.

5.4-baikal works perfectly on the same hardware (visual confirmation
2026-05-10) precisely because the request_irq call succeeds without
the ONESHOT requirement.

Revert to 5.4 behavior on PS4 hardware (or unconditionally - the
threaded variant doesn't gain anything for SCI specifically).

If v35 works:
- "SCI (IRQ9) allocation failed" gone from boot log
- "could not acquire Mutex [ACPI_MTX_Tables]" gone
- amdgpu probe doesn't see ATOM BIOS errors
- mode_set programs PLL via working ATOM
- HDMI display lights up (FINALLY)

This is THE fix.

---
--- a/drivers/acpi/osl.c
+++ b/drivers/acpi/osl.c
@@ -578,8 +578,17 @@
 
 	acpi_irq_handler = handler;
 	acpi_irq_context = context;
-	if (request_threaded_irq(irq, NULL, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED | IRQF_ONESHOT,
-			         "acpi", acpi_irq)) {
+	/* v35: PS4 - revert to non-threaded request_irq.
+	 * IRQF_ONESHOT requires that the IRQ NOT be re-enabled until the
+	 * threaded handler completes. On PS4 (Baikal southbridge) IRQ9 is
+	 * shared with something else that uses non-ONESHAOT semantics, so
+	 * shared registration of an ONESHOT handler is rejected ->
+	 * request_threaded_irq fails -> "SCI (IRQ9) allocation failed" ->
+	 * AE_NOT_ACQUIRED -> ACPI mutex initialization breaks -> ATOM BIOS
+	 * silently fails -> amdgpu PLL programming returns garbage ->
+	 * HDMI display dead. 5.4 used plain request_irq which works on
+	 * PS4. Reverting to that. */
+	if (request_irq(irq, acpi_irq, IRQF_SHARED, "acpi", acpi_irq)) {
 		pr_err("SCI (IRQ%d) allocation failed\n", irq);
 		acpi_irq_handler = NULL;
 		return AE_NOT_ACQUIRED;
